{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Act, state agencies, including those administering Medicaid (MassHealth), must respond to a public records request within 10 business days of receiving it. Within this timeframe, the agency's Records Access Officer must either grant access to the records, deny the request with a detailed explanation of the specific legal exemption being invoked (such as medical privacy laws), or provide written notice that the response will be delayed and provide an estimated date for when the records will be available.",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/how-to/make-a-public-records-request",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law (M.G.L. Chapter 66, Section 10), state agencies that administer Medicaid (MassHealth), such as the Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS), must respond to written public records requests within 10 business days of receipt. A response within this timeframe can consist of producing the records, issuing a written denial citing specific statutory exemptions (such as HIPAA or state medical privacy laws which restrict access to individual Medicaid records), or acknowledging the request and providing a compliance date for when the records will be available.",
  "source": "Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth, Public Records Division (https://www.mass.gov/orgs/public-records-supervisor)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law, state agencies (including those administering Medicaid, known as MassHealth) must respond in writing to a public records request within 10 business days of receiving it. While the agency is required to respond within this timeframe to acknowledge the request, provide a timeline for fulfillment, or deny the request (such as citing privacy exemptions for protected health information), the actual production of records may take longer if extensive gathering or redaction is required.",
  "source": "Massachusetts Public Records Access Office (Secretary of the Commonwealth), 'Public Records Law FAQs' - mass.gov",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Massachusetts Public Records Law (M.G.L. c. 66, § 10), any state agency, including MassHealth (Massachusetts's Medicaid agency), has exactly 10 business days to respond to an initial public records request. Within this 10-business-day window, the agency must either grant the request and provide the records, or deny the request in writing with a clear citation of the specific legal exemption being used (for instance, individual Medicaid beneficiary medical records are generally exempt and withheld due to HIPAA and state medical confidentiality laws). If an agency needs more time to locate or compile non-exempt records, they must notify the requester in writing of the reason for the delay and the estimated completion date.",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/guides/massachusetts-public-records-law",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Massachusetts public records law (Chapter 66, Section 20), agencies must respond to a request for public records within five business days. If additional time is needed, the agency may extend the response deadline by up to ten additional business days, provided it notifies the requester of the extension and the reason for it. This rule applies to records requests directed to the Department of Transitional Assistance, the Executive Office of Health and Human Services, and other agencies that administer Medicaid (MassHealth).",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/doc/chapter-66-public-records-law-2023/pdf",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Massachusetts public records law, agencies must respond to a request for public records, including Medicaid records, within 10 business days of receipt of the request.",
  "source": "https://www.mass.gov/public-records-law",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Rhode Island's Access to Public Records Act (APRA), state agencies (including those administering Medicaid, such as the Executive Office of Health and Human Services) have 10 business days from the receipt of a request to respond. Within this timeframe, the agency must notify the requester whether the records exist and are available, provide the records, deny the request with a justification, or state that additional time is needed (which is typically limited to a maximum extension of 20 business days). Note that while the agency must respond within 10 business days, specific personal Medicaid medical records are heavily protected and often exempt from public disclosure under HIPAA and state privacy laws, or are subject to HIPAA's 30-day timeline if requested directly by the patient for their own records.",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws § 38-2-10 (Access to Public Records Act) - https://www.rilegislature.gov/statutes/TITLE38/38-2/38-2-10.htm",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act (APRA), state agencies—including the Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS), which administers the state's Medicaid program—are required to respond to public records requests within 10 business days of receiving the request. If the agency needs additional time to locate, retrieve, or review the records for potential exemptions, they must notify the requester in writing. Please note that while the agency must acknowledge and respond to the request within 10 business days, specific personal Medicaid beneficiary medical records and financial information are generally exempt from public disclosure under federal HIPAA regulations and state privacy laws.",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws, Title 38, Chapter 38-2 (Access to Public Records Act)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act (APRA), state agencies—including the Executive Office of Health and Human Services (which oversees the state's Medicaid program)—have 10 business days to respond to a public records request. Within this initial 10-day timeframe, the agency must determine if the request complies with the law and notify the requester whether the records will be provided or withheld. While the agency can request an extension for complex or voluminous requests, they must provide written notice of this extension within the initial 10 business days.",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws § 38-2-6; Rhode Island Attorney General's Office 'Access to Public Records Act: A Guide for Citizens and Agencies'",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Rhode Island's Access to Public Records Act (APRA), state agencies, including those administering Medicaid (such as the Executive Office of Health and Human Services), have 10 business days to respond to a written public records request. Within this period, the agency must either grant access to the records, formally deny the request (typically citing HIPAA or state privacy laws for protected patient information), or notify the requester that additional time is needed to locate or review the documents.",
  "source": "Rhode Island General Laws § 38-2-7 (Access to Public Records Act) - http://webserver.rilegislature.gov/Statutes/TITLE38/38-2/38-2-7.htm",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under Rhode Island law, agencies must respond to public records requests concerning Medicaid within five business days after the request is received, unless an extension is granted for a valid reason.",
  "source": "https://www.ri.gov/records/ (Rhode Island Public Records Law, § 38-2.2)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Rhode Island law requires state agencies, including the Department of Human Services (which processes Medicaid requests), to respond to a public records request within 20 business days of receiving the request.",
  "source": "https://www.ri.gov/records/ (Rhode Island Public Records Act guidelines) and https://dhs.ri.gov/ (Department of Human Services public records policy)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Rhode Island state agencies must respond to public records requests within five (5) business days, as required by the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, and this includes requests for Medicaid records.",
  "source": "https://www.rilegislature.gov/Statutes/Titles/38/38-2-4.HTM",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "In California, public records requests regarding Medicaid (which is administered by the state as 'Medi-Cal') are governed by the California Public Records Act (CPRA). Under the CPRA, a state or local agency must respond to a request within 10 calendar days of receipt. Within this 10-day window, the agency must determine whether the request, in whole or in part, involves the disclosure of exempt records and notify the requester of that determination. Under unusual circumstances, the agency may extend this response period by an additional 14 days by providing written notice to the requester. Please note that while agencies must respond within this timeframe, specific Medi-Cal beneficiary records are typically exempt from public disclosure under strict federal (HIPAA) and state medical privacy laws.",
  "source": "State of California Department of Justice, Office of the Attorney General: Summary of the California Public Records Act (Gov. Code, § 6250 et seq.); California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) Public Records Act (CPRA) Request Guidelines",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "In California, agencies have 10 calendar days from the receipt of a public records request to determine whether they possess disclosable records and to notify the requester, in accordance with the California Public Records Act (Government Code Section 6253(c)). Medicaid is administered as Medi-Cal in California, and records held by state agencies (such as the Department of Health Care Services) or county departments are subject to this timeline. If an agency encounters unusual circumstances that prevent them from fulfilling the request within the initial 10 days, they may extend the timeframe by an additional 14 days, provided they give the requester written notice detailing the reasons for the delay.",
  "source": "https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?sectionNum=6253.&lawCode=GOV",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (CPRA), state and local agencies responsible for Medicaid (known in California as Medi-Cal), such as the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) or county welfare departments, generally have 10 days from the receipt of a public records request to make a determination on whether the records will be disclosed. If the agency needs more time due to 'unusual circumstances' (such as needing to search for records stored at a field office or off-site), they may extend this deadline by up to 14 additional calendar days, provided they give the requester written notice of the extension and the reason for it.",
  "source": "California Government Code Section 6253(c) and California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) Public Records Act Request guidelines",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (CPRA), the California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS), which administers the state's Medicaid program (Medi-Cal), has 10 days from the receipt of a request to determine whether it will comply and to notify the requester of its determination. In unusual circumstances, the agency may extend this deadline by providing notice to the requester. It is important to note that while administrative, financial, and policy records regarding Medicaid are subject to this timeline, individual Medi-Cal beneficiary records and personal health information are strictly exempt from public disclosure under both state and federal privacy laws (such as HIPAA).",
  "source": "California Public Records Act (California Government Code § 6253) and California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) Public Records Act guidelines",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act (CPRA), state agencies—including the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS), which administers California's Medicaid program (Medi-Cal)—generally have 10 calendar days from receiving a request to respond. Within this 10-day window, the agency must make a determination as to whether it has responsive records and notify the requester. If the agency requires more time to review or redact records (which is common with Medicaid files due to strict medical privacy exemptions), they must issue a written estimate of when the records will be made available. Note that while the agency must respond within this timeframe, actual patient-specific Medicaid records are typically exempt from public disclosure under federal and state medical privacy laws.",
  "source": "https://oag.ca.gov/public-records-act (California Public Records Act - Government Code Section 7922.715)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the California Public Records Act, agencies such as the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) must respond to public records requests within 10 calendar days of receipt, unless extensions are granted for clarification or to gather records.",
  "source": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/Pages/FOIA.aspx (California Department of Health Care Services FOIA page)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York State's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies have five business days from the receipt of a request to respond. Within this five business-day window, the agency must either make the requested Medicaid records available for copying, deny the request in writing with an explanation of the reasons for the denial, or provide a written acknowledgment of receipt and a reasonable estimated date for when the request will be granted or denied. (Note: While the agency must respond within this timeframe, specific individual Medicaid beneficiary records are generally exempt from public disclosure under FOIL due to strict federal HIPAA and state Social Services Law privacy protections.)",
  "source": "https://www.health.ny.gov/information_services/foil.htm",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
"answer": "Under New York State's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), state and local agencies—including the Department of Health and local Departments of Social Services that administer Medicaid—generally have five (5) business days from the receipt of a written public records request to respond. Within this five-day window, the agency must either grant the request, deny the request in writing with a specific legal justification (citing exemptions like health and patient privacy laws that protect Medicaid records), or acknowledge receipt of the request and provide a reasonable estimated date for when a final decision will be made.",
"source": "New York State Public Officers Law § 89(3) and the New York State Committee on Open Government 'FOIL Guide' (dos.ny.gov)",
"confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), state and local agencies (including those that administer Medicaid, such as the Department of Health or local Departments of Social Services) are legally required to provide a written response to a public records request within 5 business days of receipt. This initial response must either grant access to the records, deny the request, or acknowledge receipt and provide a 'reasonable' estimated date by which the records will be provided or denied. While the statute does not set a strict statutory deadline for the final production of records beyond the initial acknowledgment, state guidelines and agency policies generally consider 20 business days to be a reasonable timeframe to issue a final substantive determination. Note: Individual Medicaid beneficiary records are exempt from public disclosure under FOIL's personal privacy exemptions, so public requests typically apply to agency policies, contracts, aggregated data, or administrative records.",
  "source": "New York State Public Officers Law Article 6 (Freedom of Information Law) and the NYS Committee on Open Government FOIL Guidelines",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), agencies must respond to a request for public records, including Medicaid records, within five business days after the request is received, unless an extension is granted by the agency.",
  "source": "https://www.dos.ny.gov/foi/foi.html (New York Department of State, Freedom of Information Law – response time requirements)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York’s Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), state agencies—including those that handle Medicaid requests—must respond to a public records request within five business days, either by providing the records, denying the request, or stating that additional time is needed.",
