{
  "answer": "In Texas, state agencies—including the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC), which administers Medicaid—generally have 10 business days to respond to a written public records request. This timeframe is mandated by the Texas Public Information Act (Texas Government Code, Chapter 552).",
  "source": "https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open/what-texas-public-information-act",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (TPIA), all state agencies, including the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC) which administers Medicaid, generally have 10 business days from the date a request is received to respond. In their response, the agency must either provide the public information, explain why the information is exempt from disclosure (for instance, specific patient medical data is typically protected under HIPAA and TPIA privacy exemptions), or ask the requestor to narrow a voluminous request. Note: If you are referring to the processing time for a Medicaid benefits application rather than a public record request, the state generally has 45 days to process a standard application.",
  "source": "https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/public-information-act",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (TPIA), state agencies—including the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC), which administers the Medicaid program—generally have 10 business days to respond to a public records request. Within this 10-business-day window, the agency must either release the requested information, certify in writing that the information does not exist, or request an open records ruling from the Texas Attorney General if they intend to withhold any part of the response. Note that individual Medicaid beneficiary case files and medical records are generally exempt from public disclosure under the TPIA due to federal HIPAA and state privacy laws, though beneficiaries can request their own records through separate medical records release processes.",
  "source": "Texas Attorney General's Office - Open Government Division (The Public Information Act, Texas Government Code Chapter 552) and Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC) Public Information Request guidelines.",
  "confidence": "high"
