{
  "answer": "Under New York State's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), specifically Public Officers Law Article 6, state and local agencies (including the Department of Health and local district social services departments that administer Medicaid) have five (5) business days from the receipt of a written request to respond. Within this five-business-day window, the agency must either: (1) make the records available, (2) deny the request in writing while citing the specific legal exemption for the denial—such as protections for personal health information under federal HIPAA or New York Public Health Law § 18—or (3) provide a written acknowledgment of the request along with an estimated date for when a final determination will be made.",
  "source": "https://www.dos.ny.gov/coog/",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under New York State's Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), state and local agencies (including the Department of Health and local departments of social services that administer Medicaid) have five (5) business days to respond to a public records request. Within this timeframe, the agency must either grant access to the requested records, deny the request in writing stating the reason for denial (for example, specific patient Medicaid records are generally exempt from public disclosure under Public Health Law § 2913 due to confidentiality), or provide a written acknowledgment of receipt along with an approximate date by which the request will be granted or denied. \n\n(Note: If your question refers to the processing time for a Medicaid eligibility application for benefits rather than a public records request, local agencies generally have 45 days to make a determination, or up to 90 days if a disability determination is required.)",
  "source": "New York State Department of State, Committee on Open Government - A Guide to the Freedom of Information Law (Public Officers Law Article 6, § 87)",
  "confidence": "high"
}

{
  "answer": "Under the Texas Public Information Act (TPIA), state agencies such as the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC), which administers Medicaid, generally have 10 business days to respond to a public records request. Within this 10-business-day window, the agency must either: (1) provide the requested Medicaid records; (2) notify the requester of the cost and a realistic timeline for when the records will be available for pickup or mailing; or (3) request an open records ruling from the Texas Attorney General if the agency intends to withhold any part of the records as confidential (such as private medical or personal information protected by HIPAA or the Texas Medical Records Privacy Act).",
  "source": "Texas Government Code, Chapter 552 (Texas Public Information Act) and the Texas Attorney General's Public Information Handbook",
  "confidence": "high"
